    discussions: [
      { item:"Approval of minutes from February 23, 2026", body:"A motion to accept the minutes was made and seconded. The motion passed unanimously with all present voting in favor." },
      { item:"Parks and Recreation Impact Fee Discussion", body:"Jennifer presented information on park impact fees, noting the village currently charges $300 for single-family homes while neighboring communities charge $600-$900. The 2020 study recommended $761 but the village only increased to $300 in 2022. Plan Commission requested Parks Committee input. Committee members expressed support for a moderate increase to align with neighboring communities. Jennifer noted at current rates, Granite Ridge subdivision's 88 lots would generate $26,400 versus $52,800 at doubled rates. The committee generally supported increasing fees to be competitive while funding park improvements, with consensus favoring the moderate increase bracket rather than maximum." },
      { item:"Mock Mueller Park Master Plan RFP Selection", body:"Staff reported receiving seven proposals for the park master plan, which were reviewed by four staff members based on firm experience, personnel experience, similar projects, scope understanding, and cost. The two lowest bidders were JSD and Rettler Corporation. Roger made a motion to select Rettler Corporation, seconded by Katrina. The motion passed unanimously." },
      { item:"Yellow Banks Kayak Launch Expenses Review", body:"Jessica presented a detailed breakdown of the kayak launch project expenses and grant funding. The project received grants from DNR, Marathon County Transportation, and other sources. Lisa Beck praised the RFC document during public comment. Committee member Katrina commended Jessica and Dan Hagenbotham for their grant writing work, noting the village's out-of-pocket costs were significantly reduced. PGA Construction donated labor and equipment, and MTS donated site planning. Dan Hagenbotham will return with additional signage proposals for the Great Pineries Heritage Waterway." },
      { item:"Ice Rink Operations at Kennedy Park", body:"Staff presented information requested by committee member Katrina regarding ice rink costs and operations. The warming house has been unattended since 2020 due to COVID and subsequent staffing shortages. Everest Youth Hockey remains interested in improvements including a roofed structure. Staff noted discussions about Marathon Park's hockey facilities may increase demand for Kennedy Park ice. Katrina emphasized not wanting hockey to be forgotten amid baseball-focused Kennedy Park planning. Committee requested additional historical attendance data and user feedback for future meetings." },
    ],
    publicComment: "Jim Pinsel expressed frustration about not receiving responses to his previous comments regarding playground equipment installation, Kennedy Park fundraising updates, ice rink costs, and requested full cost accounting including staff labor hours for the ice rink. Lisa Beck thanked Michael for snow removal work during the recent blizzard and praised Sean and Jessica for the well-written Yellow Banks RFC document detailing expenses and grant funding. A written response to Jim Benson's previous email was noted for inclusion in the minutes.",
